<p>Although, if we execute this command in the server,â€¦</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">svn+ssh://root@[server_name]/root/[...] /var/www/html/[...]/releases/20100515165617 <span class="o">&amp;&amp;</span> <span class="o">(</span><span class="nb">echo </span>4 <span class="o">&gt;</span> /var/www/html/[...]/releases/20100515165617/REVISION<span class="o">)[</span>/shell]
..., funciona perfectamente.</code></pre></figure>

<p>The couse of this error is that <strong>capristano</strong> expects that the ssh protoocol authentications works unmanned using the public key of the user. But for some reason I donâ€™t know, the authentication fails.</p>

<p>To solve this problem we can use the following method:</p>

<p>In the file <strong><em>Capfile</em></strong> of our Rails project include the following line:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">default_run_options[:pty] <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">true</span>  </code></pre></figure>

<p>Setting this change and executing <strong>cap deploy</strong> capristano command ask us to type the password of the ssh connection with the server. Itâ€™s not a pretty solution, but it works.
Al aplicar este cambio y ejecutar el <strong>cap deploy</strong> capristano nos pedirÃ¡ que introduzcamos el pasword de nuestra conexiÃ³n ssh con el servidor. No es una soluciÃ³n bonita, pero funciona.</p>
